sec.p:
Pregnant ewes were monitored until vaginal delivery. When lambs were born, the ewe was allowed to lick and smell the lamb before it was dried and warmed. Newborn lambs were not intubated but if cyanosis was apparent, a face mask receiving 100% oxygen (3-5 L/min) was placed over the nostrils. Once the lamb’s condition was stabilized, indicated by regular breathing and lack of cyanosis, it was weighed, and measurements of crown-to-rump length (CRL), thoracic girth (TG), and forelimb length (FLL) were made; from these data, the ponderal index (PI; body weight/CRL
3
) was calculated. Lambs were then placed in an open-topped container under a heat source. Within 1 to 2 hours of birth, lambs were fed colostrum expressed from the ewe.
